content.text:
Yes, but in Tailwind 4 you do not add `@tailwindcss/container-queries`.

Container queries are built in. The Tailwind 3 setup:

```ts
import tailwindContainerQueries from "@tailwindcss/container-queries";

theme: {
  extend: {
    containers: {
      xs: "20rem",
      sm: "40rem",
      // ...
    },
  },
},
plugins: [tailwindContainerQueries]
```

becomes CSS-first config in `globals.css`:

```css
@theme inline {
  --container-xs: 20rem;
  --container-sm: 40rem;
  --container-md: 60rem;
  --container-lg: 80rem;
  --container-xl: 100rem;
  --container-2xl: 150rem;
}
```

Then the component still works as originally intended:

```tsx
<div className="w-full @container">
  <div className="grid gap-4 @xs:grid-cols-1 @sm:grid-cols-2 @md:grid-cols-3 @xl:grid-cols-4 @2xl:grid-cols-6">
    ...
  </div>
</div>
```

So the “container setup” is two parts:

1. Mark a parent with `@container`.
2. Define custom container breakpoint tokens with `--container-*` in `@theme`.

I also added the app shell utilities in `globals.css` via Tailwind 4 `@utility`, which is the right equivalent for those wrapper/container/scroll classes.

**Clarifying Tailwind 4 usage**

I need to provide a concise answer, mentioning the lack of plugins and the inline use of @theme. It’s important to note that Tailwind 4 uses @tailwindcss/vite without requiring a tailwind config. I should explain how to achieve this with @theme --container-* in globals and the built-in @container class. I can mention that plugins are only needed for v3.2 and that our current values might alter defaults. Finally, I should keep it brief.

Correct: in Tailwind v4, `@tailwindcss/container-queries` is no longer needed. Container queries are built into core.

So this v3 config:

```ts
plugins: [tailwindcssAnimate, tailwindContainerQueries]
```

becomes no plugin setup in v4. You just use:

```tsx
<div className="@container">
  <div className="@sm:grid-cols-2 @md:grid-cols-3">...</div>
</div>
```

For custom container sizes, v4 uses CSS theme variables:

```css
@theme {
  --container-xs: 20rem;
  --container-sm: 40rem;
  --container-md: 60rem;
  --container-lg: 80rem;
  --container-xl: 100rem;
  --container-2xl: 150rem;
}
```

This matches Tailwind’s v4 docs: container queries are “first-class APIs... no plugins required,” and custom sizes use `--container-*` theme variables. See [Tailwind v4 container queries](https://tailwindcss.com/blog/tailwindcss-v4#container-queries) and [container query docs](https://tailwindcss.com/docs/responsive-design#container-queries).
